{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"785"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/785"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.04,0.11,0.35,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40168"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/785"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40392"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40168"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a two month history of a painless swelling on the right side of his face. He has no other symptoms. On examination there is a firm, 2 cm well defined subcutaneous swelling immediately in front of the tragus. The skin moves freely over the swelling and there is some drooping of the corner of his mouth on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pleomorphic adenoma of the parotid","Wharton\u0027s duct calculus","Warthin\u0027s tumour","Carcinoma of the parotid","Chronic sialectasis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question points to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the parotid\u003C/strong\u003E as the most likely diagnosis, for a number of reasons. Firstly, the swelling is in the region of the parotid gland and it should be assumed that the swelling arises from this gland until proven otherwise. The drooping at the corner of the mouth suggests involvement of a branch of the facial nerve - and this nerve travels through the parotid gland (between the superficial and deep lobes). A facial nerve palsy, however minor, immediately suggests that the most likely cause for this patient\u0027s problem is some form of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphic adenoma of the parotid\u003C/strong\u003E would most commonly present as a solitary smooth, mobile, painless mass which slowly enlarges. Furthermore, a pleomorphic adenoma would be less likely to cause a facial nerve palsy, although a large adenoma could have a mass effect - but this is a relatively small tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EWharton\u0027s duct calculus\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a stone obstructing the outflow tract of the submandibular duct (AKA Wharton\u0027s duct). This condition would present with pain in the submandibular area, making such a diagnosis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarthin\u0027s tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are benign, sharply demarcated tumours of the salivary gland, most commonly arising in the tail of the gland. They are the second most common benign tumours of the parotid, behind pleomorphic adenomas, with which they present essentially identically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic sialectasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to long-standing dilatation of the salivary glands, which most commonly presents following an infection of the parotid gland (parotitis) which causes subsequent parotid gland destruction. This condition would be more likely to present with a longer history of the presence of the swelling and a more diffuse swelling in the area of the parotid gland.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Facial nerve palsies associated with unilateral cheek swelling should raise suspicion for parotid malignancy"],"references":["Agrawal A, Singh V, Kumar P, Bhagol A, Narwal A, Singh I. Unilateral swelling of cheek. National Journal of Maxillofacial Surgery. 2017 Jul;8(2):157."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"785"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-31T08:35:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T15:01:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"785"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40168"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n